NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
GEORGIA; 
</P>
<P>
QUADRIPLEGIC PLEADS FOR BETTER STATE CARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A quadriplegic who won court permission to shut off his life-sustaining 
ventilator told lawmakers in Atlanta that the state's way of caring for the 
severely disabled was a big reason behind his wish to die. 
</P>
<P>
Larry McAfee, 34, appeared before the Georgia Senate to plead for changes in 
care for the disabled, which he called obsolete and cruel. Although he has 
changed his mind and decided to live, McAfee said the quality of his life since 
he was paralyzed in 1985 has been poor, primarily because he has been in 
institutions. McAfee said the state should adopt programs of independent living 
for the disabled and should not send them to out-of-state nursing homes. 
</P>
