LOCAL; 
</P>
<P>
DECISION ON LANDFILL DELAYED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Los Angeles Regional Planning Commission today delayed a decision on the 
proposed expansion of the Sunshine Canyon landfill near Granada Hills because 
of incomplete environmental studies. 
</P>
<P>
Browning-Ferris Industries, which operates the 230-acre dump north of Granada 
Hills, has proposed an expansion to include 542 acres of land in unincorporated 
county territory. 
</P>
<P>
The commission voted 4 to 0 to delay making a decision after Deputy County 
Counsel Charles J. Moore advised members that BFI needed to conduct more 
thorough studies of alternative landfill sites in the county and on property 
the firm owns in the city of Los Angeles adjacent to the existing landfill. 
</P>
<P>
County planners, who urged commissioners to decide the issue today, said it 
would take up to two months to complete additional studies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
