</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chicago Board of Health has proposed a ban on cigarette advertising on 
outdoor billboards, buses, trains and taxicabs, the Chicago Sun-Times reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
The board voted unanimously Wednesday to draft an ordinance that could be 
presented to the City Council as early as next month. 
</P>
<P>
The proposal came on the heels of a new federal anti-smoking proposal. 
</P>
<P>
Billboard companies said they will form an advisory council to negotiate 
voluntary restrictions on tobacco and alcohol ads around schools, as well as to 
guide anti-drug ad campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
"Why would cigarette companies spend money putting up billboards? They must 
feel it's effective advertising," board President Whitney Addington said. "I 
think it's such a health threat that the Board of Health has to fight it." 
</P>
