<P>
DOUG DRABEK WINS $775,000 INCREASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PITTSBURGH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Right-hander Doug Drabek won his salary case today, earning a $775,000 pay 
raise and giving the players a 5-3 edge over the Pittsburgh Pirates in 
arbitration hearings. 
</P>
<P>
Drabek, who is 29-19 the last two seasons, will get $1.1 million this season 
instead of the Pirates' $750,000 offer. Drabek made $325,000 in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Last season, Drabek was 14-12 with a 2.80 earned run average in 35 appearances, 
all but one of them starts for the fifth-place Pirates. He had five shutouts 
among his eight complete games and earned a save in his only relief appearance. 
He struck out 123 and walked 69 in 244.1 innings. 
</P>
